<h1>@HI{{aru}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @N1{{location}} @HI{{ni}} @HI{{ha}} @N2{{}} @HI{{ga}} @EM{{@HI{{aru}}}}
<li> @N1{{}} @HI{{ha}} @N2{{location}} @HI{{ni}} @EM{{@HI{{aru}}}}
<li> @EM{{@HI{{aru}}}} <em>predicate</em>
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
In the first sentence pattern, a location is presented as the topic and @EM{{@HI{{aru}}}}
focuses on what exists. @HI{{ni}} may be dropped.
</p>

<p>
In the second sentence pattern, a thing is presented as the topic and @EM{{@HI{{aru}}}}
focuses on where that thing is.
</p>

<p>
Note that @EM{{@HI{{aru}}}} uses @HI{{ga}} to mark its object and not @HI{{wo}}.
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{aru}}}} is only used to express the existence or possession of inanimate things.
For animate things, <a href="grammar-iru.html">@HI{{iru}}</a> is used.
</p>

<p>
The negative form of @EM{{@HI{{aru}}}} is @HI{{nai}}.
</p>

<p>
When @EM{{@HI{{aru}}}} is used to indicate having an animate object,
that object must have a close connection with the possessor.
</p>

<p>
When @EM{{@HI{{aru}}}} is used to for an event such as a party, @HI{{de}}
rather than @HI{{ni}} must be used.
</p>

